But also, our pets
are continually

00:13:08.170 --> 00:13:10.760
proven to make us healthier.

00:13:10.760 --> 00:13:14.850
And this isn't just wishy-washy
stuff that, you know,

00:13:14.850 --> 00:13:17.380
I feel better when
I'm around a dog.

00:13:17.380 --> 00:13:21.050
It's actually hard,
scientific fact

00:13:21.050 --> 00:13:23.040
that pets have a
positive influence

00:13:23.040 --> 00:13:24.800
in our health at all ages.

00:13:24.800 --> 00:13:30.270
So for kids, as young
as one year of age,

00:13:30.270 --> 00:13:33.810
having a pet in the house
results in a reduced

00:13:33.810 --> 00:13:39.120
risk ear infections, reduced
reliance on antibiotics,

00:13:39.120 --> 00:13:43.890
reduced level of asthma, and
also, reduced level of colds

00:13:43.890 --> 00:13:44.390
as well.

00:13:44.390 --> 00:13:49.450
So that's an amazing
statistic, when you look at it,

00:13:49.450 --> 00:13:51.620
and it's backed up by a
number of different studies.

00:13:51.620 --> 00:13:54.640
When you go into
adults, our pets

00:13:54.640 --> 00:13:58.760
have a very dramatic effect
on our cardiovascular health.

00:13:58.760 --> 00:14:03.027
So we're generally fitter and
healthier if we own animals.

00:14:03.027 --> 00:14:04.860
They've actually been
proven in some studies

00:14:04.860 --> 00:14:08.470
to-- despite not
wearing activewear,

00:14:08.470 --> 00:14:11.370
they're actually the most
effective personal trainers

00:14:11.370 --> 00:14:13.300
out there.

00:14:13.300 --> 00:14:15.130
And I'll get to why
that is, in a second.

00:14:15.130 --> 00:14:17.160
But for the
elderly-- personally,

00:14:17.160 --> 00:14:19.780
I think the facts
around the elderly

00:14:19.780 --> 00:14:21.640
are probably the most dramatic.

00:14:21.640 --> 00:14:26.740
Because the elderly-- people,
say, over the age of 65,

00:14:26.740 --> 00:14:28.010
visit the doctor less.

00:14:28.010 --> 00:14:32.300
They make fewer hospital visits,
they take less medication,

00:14:32.300 --> 00:14:35.370
and they experience less
loneliness, if they have a pet.

00:14:35.370 --> 00:14:38.790
And when you consider
our aging population,

00:14:38.790 --> 00:14:41.290
and you consider what our
health budgets look like,

00:14:41.290 --> 00:14:44.220
and you realize just
how much money has

00:14:44.220 --> 00:14:47.930
to be put into supporting
our elderly, you think, wow,

00:14:47.930 --> 00:14:51.670
for the price of a bowl
of dog food each day,

00:14:51.670 --> 00:14:54.350
you could actually have that
positive health benefit.

00:14:54.350 --> 00:14:58.180
I just think, to me,
it's an amazing trade-off

00:14:58.180 --> 00:15:02.520
to be able to offer that.

00:15:02.520 --> 00:15:09.070
There's a lot of science around
why those benefits exist.

00:15:09.070 --> 00:15:12.560
You can probably condense
it down to two things,

00:15:12.560 --> 00:15:15.730
in terms of the health benefits.

00:15:15.730 --> 00:15:18.290
It's really the
constant exposure

00:15:18.290 --> 00:15:20.410
to non-threatening bugs.

00:15:20.410 --> 00:15:22.470
So if you're around
a dog, you're

00:15:22.470 --> 00:15:26.380
getting bombarded with
non-threatening bugs that

00:15:26.380 --> 00:15:27.710
really struggle to infect you.

00:15:27.710 --> 00:15:30.640
So your immune system
becomes hard and fast

00:15:30.640 --> 00:15:32.600
at recognizing
bacteria and viruses,

00:15:32.600 --> 00:15:35.410
and dodging it, weaving
it, working out how

00:15:35.410 --> 00:15:37.350
to deal with it, and moving on.

00:15:37.350 --> 00:15:39.830
So constant exposure to
non-threatening bugs--

00:15:39.830 --> 00:15:42.640
and in terms of the
health benefits,

00:15:42.640 --> 00:15:45.080
it's constant exposure to
non-threatening bugging

00:15:45.080 --> 00:15:47.340
from them wanting a walk.

00:15:47.340 --> 00:15:50.380
It's very hard to
say, no, to a dog that

00:15:50.380 --> 00:15:54.170
is sitting in front of you,
begging you to go for a walk.

00:15:54.170 --> 00:15:56.300
And as a result, we give in.

00:15:56.300 --> 00:16:01.215
But it's a compromise that has
really significant benefits

00:16:01.215 --> 00:16:01.840
for each of us.

00:16:04.720 --> 00:16:08.640
One of the-- I'm exposed to
hundreds of different studies

00:16:08.640 --> 00:16:11.150
every year, and the one I
love-- it actually came out

00:16:11.150 --> 00:16:12.260
a couple of years ago.

00:16:12.260 --> 00:16:15.200
And it was from Kyoto
University in Japan.

00:16:15.200 --> 00:16:17.850
Now, I love the Japanese.

00:16:17.850 --> 00:16:20.700
They can come up with some
really interesting research,

00:16:20.700 --> 00:16:22.770
but this research
centered around--

00:16:22.770 --> 00:16:26.297
they wanted to work
out whether how

00:16:26.297 --> 00:16:28.630
we love our pets, whether
it's just us saying it-- is it

00:16:28.630 --> 00:16:29.838
just something we talk about?

00:16:29.838 --> 00:16:33.640
Do we just love our pets because
they're there, they're cute,

00:16:33.640 --> 00:16:36.550
and they give us
extra Instagram likes?

00:16:36.550 --> 00:16:38.620
Or is it something
more tangible?

00:16:38.620 --> 00:16:42.250
And they actually put
owners into a room,

00:16:42.250 --> 00:16:43.370
and they monitored.

00:16:43.370 --> 00:16:45.820
They actually took samples
from them-- samples of saliva--

00:16:45.820 --> 00:16:47.820
and measured their
hormonal levels.

00:16:47.820 --> 00:16:51.540
What they found is, when they
brought their pets in and put

00:16:51.540 --> 00:16:54.350
their pets in front of them
and let them pat their pets,

00:16:54.350 --> 00:16:57.320
they released a
hormone, consistently.

00:16:57.320 --> 00:16:59.550
And that hormone is oxytocin.

00:16:59.550 --> 00:17:03.425
And oxytocin, if you
know what that is,

00:17:03.425 --> 00:17:06.640
is actually the hormone
that we, as humans,

00:17:06.640 --> 00:17:09.119
release when we
see our loved ones

00:17:09.119 --> 00:17:11.760
and when we see our children.

00:17:11.760 --> 00:17:13.869
So it's a chemical thing.

00:17:13.869 --> 00:17:14.560
It's real.

00:17:14.560 --> 00:17:17.319
The love for a pet is very real.

00:17:17.319 --> 00:17:18.819
The flip side of
that, which I love,

00:17:18.819 --> 00:17:21.579
is the fact that they
then did the opposite,

00:17:21.579 --> 00:17:27.079
and actually measured the
levels in dogs and in pets.

00:17:27.079 --> 00:17:29.080
And guess what?

00:17:29.080 --> 00:17:30.200
It goes both ways.

00:17:30.200 --> 00:17:32.456
They actually release
the hormone as well--

00:17:32.456 --> 00:17:33.130
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:33.130 --> 00:17:34.838
--which is, kind of,
reassuring in a way.

00:17:34.838 --> 00:17:36.430
They're not cheating on you.

00:17:39.430 --> 00:17:42.890
So it's a very special
thing, but it's also

00:17:42.890 --> 00:17:44.502
a very tangible thing.

00:17:44.502 --> 00:17:46.710
And so you're getting a
picture, I guess, of the fact

00:17:46.710 --> 00:17:50.010
that there are benefits
across the line,

00:17:50.010 --> 00:17:52.370
in terms of the physical
health benefits.

00:17:52.370 --> 00:17:56.390
But I think a really
powerful benefit out there

00:17:56.390 --> 00:17:59.460
in the community, which is often
undervalued but is becoming

00:17:59.460 --> 00:18:02.760
more researched
and more recognized

00:18:02.760 --> 00:18:04.960
is the benefit on mental health.

00:18:04.960 --> 00:18:07.090
And you'll see a lot
of dogs out there

00:18:07.090 --> 00:18:10.060
that are in the role of being
assistance dogs or therapy

00:18:10.060 --> 00:18:11.080
dogs.

00:18:11.080 --> 00:18:15.880
And the work they're doing
currently with kids with autism

00:18:15.880 --> 00:18:16.920
is quite remarkable.

00:18:16.920 --> 00:18:23.020
We're still not exactly clear
why pets and animals-- dogs,

00:18:23.020 --> 00:18:24.940
horses, all sorts of
different animals--

00:18:24.940 --> 00:18:26.740
have a positive effect
on kids with autism.

00:18:26.740 --> 00:18:29.070
But the belief is that
it changes the brain wave

00:18:29.070 --> 00:18:33.170
activity and results in a more
controlled brain wave activity.

00:18:35.840 --> 00:18:40.440
I've had the pleasure of having
a client at work who suffers

00:18:40.440 --> 00:18:42.230
from extreme schizophrenia.

00:18:42.230 --> 00:18:46.210
And he has been in therapy,
he's been institutionalized,

00:18:46.210 --> 00:18:48.950
and he's been on
multiple medications

00:18:48.950 --> 00:18:51.180
over a number of years.

00:18:51.180 --> 00:18:55.110
But about seven years ago, he
got two dogs, Oscar and Dudley.

00:18:55.110 --> 00:18:59.005
And he comes into the clinic,
about, every three days,

00:18:59.005 --> 00:19:00.990
and just loves it.

00:19:00.990 --> 00:19:03.230
He always turns up
with these two dogs.

00:19:03.230 --> 00:19:05.480
And I had the pleasure of
talking to one of his carers

00:19:05.480 --> 00:19:09.510
the other day, and I said,
oh, talk to me about the dogs.

00:19:09.510 --> 00:19:13.230
And they said, hands down,
the most positive effect

00:19:13.230 --> 00:19:15.190
on his life hasn't
been medication,

00:19:15.190 --> 00:19:17.090
has not been our
hospital system.

00:19:17.090 --> 00:19:18.706
It's been those two dogs.

00:19:18.706 --> 00:19:21.920
Because in his extreme
schizophrenic state,

00:19:21.920 --> 00:19:24.240
where he has disordered
thoughts and isn't

00:19:24.240 --> 00:19:28.510
really sure about what he's
doing next, what those dogs do

00:19:28.510 --> 00:19:32.440
is provide him with a very
clear path and a very clear plan

00:19:32.440 --> 00:19:33.660
for his day.

00:19:33.660 --> 00:19:36.350
And his day starts by getting
them up, getting them outside,

00:19:36.350 --> 00:19:38.540
going to the bathroom,
and feeding them.

00:19:38.540 --> 00:19:41.520
And the whole day is
built around these dogs,

00:19:41.520 --> 00:19:43.330
and he goes out and
takes them for a walk.

00:19:43.330 --> 00:19:48.320
And they say that without fail,
those dogs have saved his life,

00:19:48.320 --> 00:19:50.430
but also turned his life around.

00:19:50.430 --> 00:19:53.650
And these are just
two dogs who seem

00:19:53.650 --> 00:19:56.710
to, like a lot of
animals that I deal with

00:19:56.710 --> 00:20:00.260
and a lot of animals that I see
in therapy situations or even

00:20:00.260 --> 00:20:02.920
just in your everyday
home, seem to know

00:20:02.920 --> 00:20:04.120
what's required of them.

00:20:04.120 --> 00:20:06.700
And that's a really, I
think, undervalued thing

00:20:06.700 --> 00:20:07.950
with our pets.

00:20:07.950 --> 00:20:08.870
Somehow, they know.

00:20:08.870 --> 00:20:11.720
Somehow, they seem to
sense when you're happy,

00:20:11.720 --> 00:20:13.320
they seem to sense
when you're sad,

00:20:13.320 --> 00:20:15.830
and they seem to know
when is the right time

00:20:15.830 --> 00:20:19.787
to put that little
nose on your lap,

00:20:19.787 --> 00:20:21.870
when's the right time to
just give you some space,

00:20:21.870 --> 00:20:24.660
or when's the right time to
try to turn your mood around.

00:20:24.660 --> 00:20:29.420
And I think that's a really,
really special thing.

00:20:29.420 --> 00:20:35.122
So I would hope that given
the fact that in Australia, we

00:20:35.122 --> 00:20:36.580
do pride ourselves
in being a world

00:20:36.580 --> 00:20:38.900
leader in a number
of different areas,

00:20:38.900 --> 00:20:41.930
I would hope that we
can somehow reverse

00:20:41.930 --> 00:20:43.456
this trend, where
we're not a world

00:20:43.456 --> 00:20:44.580
leader in pet-friendliness.

00:20:44.580 --> 00:20:47.030
We gave you some of
the scores there,

00:20:47.030 --> 00:20:50.930
and the fact that
Sydney was 15 out of 16

00:20:50.930 --> 00:20:52.820
in the pet-friendly
scores-- well,

00:20:52.820 --> 00:20:55.930
Australia ranks right
down, quite low,

00:20:55.930 --> 00:20:57.340
overall, as a country.

00:20:57.340 --> 00:21:00.670
So it's something we
do need to look at.

00:21:00.670 --> 00:21:02.480
And as I said, Europe
and North America

00:21:02.480 --> 00:21:04.100
are, kind of, your
gold standard.

00:21:04.100 --> 00:21:07.530
And they're not experiencing
this issue with pet population

00:21:07.530 --> 00:21:10.030
decline like we are.

00:21:10.030 --> 00:21:13.520
I was in Canada towards
the end of last year,

00:21:13.520 --> 00:21:15.820
staying in a nice
hotel for work,

00:21:15.820 --> 00:21:17.870
and as I was
walking to the lift,

00:21:17.870 --> 00:21:19.610
a golden retriever
walked into the lift

00:21:19.610 --> 00:21:22.480
with me, with its owner,
and went up to its room.

00:21:22.480 --> 00:21:25.370
And you know, I wasn't
deterred by that.

00:21:25.370 --> 00:21:26.070
I loved it.

00:21:26.070 --> 00:21:29.645
But this hotel was quite
happy to have animal guests.

00:21:32.710 --> 00:21:34.310
Anyone that's traveled
to France will

00:21:34.310 --> 00:21:35.950
know that when
you go into cafes,

00:21:35.950 --> 00:21:39.930
it's not out of the ordinary
to sit up next to a poodle

00:21:39.930 --> 00:21:41.390
while you have your croissant.

00:21:41.390 --> 00:21:44.470
And I think, far from
detracting from the experience,

00:21:44.470 --> 00:21:45.720
it actually adds to it.

00:21:45.720 --> 00:21:50.460
It actually makes it more of
a pleasant, cultural moment

00:21:50.460 --> 00:21:51.490
to enjoy.

00:21:51.490 --> 00:21:54.580
So I guess we have to
look at, why is that?

00:21:54.580 --> 00:22:00.580
Why do those countries decide
to focus on the positives

00:22:00.580 --> 00:22:03.840
rather than fear the negatives.

00:22:03.840 --> 00:22:08.640
I think, sometimes, in
Australia, we can do that.

00:22:08.640 --> 00:22:11.560
A classic example-- I'm not
sure if you followed in the news

00:22:11.560 --> 00:22:15.360
the fact that a few months ago,
the newly formed Inner West

00:22:15.360 --> 00:22:20.020
Council in Sydney decided
to ban dogs from the pubs.

00:22:20.020 --> 00:22:21.670
So after years and
years and years

00:22:21.670 --> 00:22:25.610
of dogs being allowed to go
into pubs around Balmain,

00:22:25.610 --> 00:22:28.670
all of a sudden, the
council decided, no.

00:22:28.670 --> 00:22:32.860
On occupational health
and safety grounds,

00:22:32.860 --> 00:22:35.650
the dogs would now
no longer be allowed

00:22:35.650 --> 00:22:39.720
around food areas-- so not
allowed in any part of the pub.

00:22:39.720 --> 00:22:41.760
The absurdity of
that is something

00:22:41.760 --> 00:22:43.770
that grabs me straight away.

00:22:43.770 --> 00:22:47.090
When you can see
that on a health--

00:22:47.090 --> 00:22:50.720
if a health basis is
what's being used there,

00:22:50.720 --> 00:22:53.430
pets have their bugs
and we have ours.

00:22:53.430 --> 00:22:56.020
It's actually very hard
for those to cross over.

00:22:56.020 --> 00:23:02.110
So to think that there's a
health risk around pets being

00:23:02.110 --> 00:23:05.400
in a restaurant or near where
people are eating food--

00:23:05.400 --> 00:23:09.230
it's far more dangerous to have
a person being near the food

00:23:09.230 --> 00:23:12.178
than it is to have a
dog being near the food.

00:23:12.178 --> 00:23:17.790
I'm hesitant to say this when
there's a couple cameras on,

00:23:17.790 --> 00:23:20.320
but it would be far
more safe for me

00:23:20.320 --> 00:23:24.040
to have a dog lick my face and
lick my mouth than a person I

00:23:24.040 --> 00:23:24.620
don't know.

00:23:24.620 --> 00:23:25.770
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:25.770 --> 00:23:27.950
I'm not going to give a
demonstration right now,

00:23:27.950 --> 00:23:32.410
but that is a simple
scientific fact.

00:23:32.410 --> 00:23:37.380
And so it's an interesting
mental image, to be honest.

00:23:37.380 --> 00:23:41.540
But it does stack up,
time and time again,

00:23:41.540 --> 00:23:42.795
on scientific studies.

00:23:45.087 --> 00:23:46.920
People are very passionate
about their pets,

00:23:46.920 --> 00:23:50.020
so I've been encouraged
by the push-back

00:23:50.020 --> 00:23:53.870
on that idea of banning the
pets in pubs in Balmain.

00:23:53.870 --> 00:23:56.200
But continually,
I do find, there

00:23:56.200 --> 00:23:57.890
are little moments
in our society,

00:23:57.890 --> 00:23:59.280
where we have to check it.

00:23:59.280 --> 00:24:03.070
And we have to have a look at it
and go, hang on, is that right?

00:24:03.070 --> 00:24:05.060
Banning the pets
in the pubs is one,

00:24:05.060 --> 00:24:07.520
but we even had an
example last month,

00:24:07.520 --> 00:24:12.766
with the census, that
highly successful census.

00:24:12.766 --> 00:24:14.750
[LAUGHTER]

00:24:14.750 --> 00:24:18.240
So what we had there
was-- in the past,

00:24:18.240 --> 00:24:21.440
some census in some
years have actually

00:24:21.440 --> 00:24:23.280
included questions about pets.

00:24:23.280 --> 00:24:24.740
How many pets do
we have out there?

00:24:24.740 --> 00:24:26.580
What pets do people own?

00:24:26.580 --> 00:24:29.200
This year-- not a
single question.

00:24:29.200 --> 00:24:32.120
So considering that the
pets are such a huge part

00:24:32.120 --> 00:24:34.860
of our communities, how
can we possibly plan

00:24:34.860 --> 00:24:36.840
for communities involving
pets if we don't even

00:24:36.840 --> 00:24:40.530
know how many pets there are
out there and where they live?

00:24:40.530 --> 00:24:44.030
So as a result of that, I
launched my own pet census

00:24:44.030 --> 00:24:48.320
that night, almost in defiance.

00:24:48.320 --> 00:24:51.680
And 100,000 people filled
it out in the space

00:24:51.680 --> 00:24:55.730
of 48 hours, which is a
remarkable contribution

00:24:55.730 --> 00:24:59.859
of people clearly recognizing
that that's not quite right.

00:24:59.859 --> 00:25:01.650
But it also shows how
passionate people are

00:25:01.650 --> 00:25:04.190
and how willing people are
to make sure that their pets'

00:25:04.190 --> 00:25:07.590
voices are heard.

00:25:07.590 --> 00:25:10.250
And amongst all of
the different data

00:25:10.250 --> 00:25:12.000
about how many different
pets people owned

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:14.582
and where they lived and where
they exercised their pets,

00:25:14.582 --> 00:25:16.290
there were some really
interesting things

00:25:16.290 --> 00:25:21.540
which really show how much love
there is for animals out there.

00:25:21.540 --> 00:25:28.900
40% of people share their
beds with their pets.

00:25:28.900 --> 00:25:32.090
I was just talking before
about sharing saliva.

00:25:32.090 --> 00:25:36.660
That's a lot of pillows being
shared and a lot of wet patches

00:25:36.660 --> 00:25:38.800
that-- on the pillow--
you can't quite explain.

00:25:38.800 --> 00:25:41.174
And you just go back to sleep
and think, well, hopefully,

00:25:41.174 --> 00:25:42.770
it's my drool and not his.

00:25:42.770 --> 00:25:48.040
So the other thing was, what's
the most affectionate way

00:25:48.040 --> 00:25:50.540
that people show their
love for their pets?

00:25:50.540 --> 00:25:53.410
I asked the question, do
people pat, do they hug,

00:25:53.410 --> 00:25:54.785
or do they kiss?

00:25:54.785 --> 00:25:58.700
The most popular was the kiss.

00:25:58.700 --> 00:26:03.230
I think it was 40%, then
30% for the other two.

00:26:03.230 --> 00:26:06.590
So there is a lot of love.

00:26:06.590 --> 00:26:10.356
And so hopefully, if
government, at a federal level,

00:26:10.356 --> 00:26:11.980
at a state level,
and at a local level,

00:26:11.980 --> 00:26:15.930
can recognize the fact that pets
do make a huge contribution out

00:26:15.930 --> 00:26:18.494
there, that they deserve
to be recognized,

00:26:18.494 --> 00:26:20.535
that they deserve to be
given their little slice,

00:26:20.535 --> 00:26:23.946
and that they deserve to
be given the pat in return

00:26:23.946 --> 00:26:27.700
for what they contribute to
our society, to our health,

00:26:27.700 --> 00:26:30.030
and to our well-being--
and consistently, I

00:26:30.030 --> 00:26:32.430
find that the more we
give them, the more they

00:26:32.430 --> 00:26:34.750
give us back in return.

00:26:34.750 --> 00:26:38.260
If people are worried about pets
barking during the day, when

00:26:38.260 --> 00:26:40.270
you're at work,
well, funnily enough,

00:26:40.270 --> 00:26:42.420
access to an exercise
area in the morning

00:26:42.420 --> 00:26:45.380
before you go to work may just
be the best cure for that.

00:26:45.380 --> 00:26:50.710
So if we actually help them
out, and help them help us,

00:26:50.710 --> 00:26:52.220
then often, we're better off.

00:26:52.220 --> 00:26:55.050
So I am encouraged
to come in here

00:26:55.050 --> 00:26:59.517
and see these four-legged
friends sharing

00:26:59.517 --> 00:27:00.350
the office with you.

00:27:00.350 --> 00:27:02.516
Obviously, Google's
right on board.

00:27:02.516 --> 00:27:04.390
And hopefully, more and
more people out there

00:27:04.390 --> 00:27:07.056
will recognize the importance of
keeping Australia pet-friendly.

00:27:07.056 --> 00:27:08.655
So thank you for your time.

00:27:08.655 --> 00:27:11.070
And I look forward to
talking with you after this,

00:27:11.070 --> 00:27:13.350
about your own concerns.

00:27:13.350 --> 00:27:13.850
Thank you.

00:27:13.850 --> 00:27:15.884
[APPLAUSE]

00:27:22.172 --> 00:27:23.380
SPEAKER: Thank you very much.

00:27:23.380 --> 00:27:24.190
That was fantastic.

00:27:24.190 --> 00:27:27.122
I like the idea of
having a pet census.

00:27:27.122 --> 00:27:28.580
Because I know my
girlfriend and I,

00:27:28.580 --> 00:27:30.880
we argue about whether or
not the cat and the dog

00:27:30.880 --> 00:27:32.092
can go in the bed.

00:27:32.092 --> 00:27:34.050
And so I think the 40%
is about representative.

00:27:34.050 --> 00:27:36.091
We sort of have an argument
about that each time.

00:27:36.091 --> 00:27:38.260
CHRIS BROWN: It
was 40% on the bed.

00:27:38.260 --> 00:27:41.195
It was another 25%
in the bedroom.

00:27:41.195 --> 00:27:43.070
So you can find, like,
a compromise position,

00:27:43.070 --> 00:27:46.370
where they have their
own bed next to the bed.

00:27:46.370 --> 00:27:48.074
But we all know how that ends.

00:27:48.074 --> 00:27:49.490
[LAUGHTER]

00:27:49.490 --> 00:27:53.362
At about midnight,
there's a little, sort of,

00:27:53.362 --> 00:27:55.070
slow crawl upwards--
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:27:55.070 --> 00:27:55.215
SPEAKER: Exactly.

00:27:55.215 --> 00:27:57.970
And then, they're, like, up by
the pillow in a few seconds.

00:27:57.970 --> 00:27:58.471
Yeah.

00:27:58.471 --> 00:28:00.011
CHRIS BROWN: I know--
and look, maybe

00:28:00.011 --> 00:28:01.965
I'm, sort of, looking
towards the future here,

00:28:01.965 --> 00:28:05.810
but I know plenty of
people who have been told--

00:28:05.810 --> 00:28:10.330
and I hate to put words in your
mouth-- that it's either you

00:28:10.330 --> 00:28:12.490
or the dog in the bed.

00:28:12.490 --> 00:28:14.520
So you know, you can choose.

00:28:14.520 --> 00:28:15.788
That's just how it goes.

00:28:15.788 --> 00:28:16.454
SPEAKER: I know.

00:28:16.454 --> 00:28:16.518
I know.

00:28:16.518 --> 00:28:19.130
So I don't mind the cat sort of,
roaming, but the dog, for me,

00:28:19.130 --> 00:28:19.960
has to be towards the end.

00:28:19.960 --> 00:28:21.520
But look, you know,
these are things.

00:28:21.520 --> 00:28:23.500
But we did our own
little survey here.

00:28:23.500 --> 00:28:25.850
We had the Bring Your Dog
to Work Day last week.

00:28:25.850 --> 00:28:27.430
And we, sort of, asked
people at the end of it,

00:28:27.430 --> 00:28:28.888
you know, what did
you find useful?

00:28:28.888 --> 00:28:29.840
How did it all go?

00:28:29.840 --> 00:28:32.410
And 50% of people said, they
found that public transport

00:28:32.410 --> 00:28:33.740
was a big challenge for them.

00:28:33.740 --> 00:28:36.050
So they like actually found
it hard to get their dogs

00:28:36.050 --> 00:28:36.850
even to the office.

00:28:36.850 --> 00:28:39.120
So they wanted to bring
them, but they couldn't.

00:28:39.120 --> 00:28:40.170
You know, the
conversations you're

00:28:40.170 --> 00:28:42.420
having with the government,
and that sort of thing--

00:28:42.420 --> 00:28:44.000
how are you finding
their responding

00:28:44.000 --> 00:28:46.630
to that sort of challenge, like
trains, the buses, and ferries?

00:28:46.630 --> 00:28:47.380
CHRIS BROWN: Yeah.

00:28:47.380 --> 00:28:52.520
I guess, the key message
out of any of this push

00:28:52.520 --> 00:28:57.970
to open up the avenues for pets
to be more included in society

00:28:57.970 --> 00:28:59.530
is that it does go both ways.

00:28:59.530 --> 00:29:01.280
People have to be
responsible, and they

00:29:01.280 --> 00:29:03.240
have to be good
owners, and they have

00:29:03.240 --> 00:29:05.440
to pick up after their pets.

00:29:05.440 --> 00:29:11.090
If you have a dog that wants to
jump up and hug and, you know,

00:29:11.090 --> 00:29:13.660
tongue pash every
single person it meets,

00:29:13.660 --> 00:29:17.360
and it weighs 60 kilos, maybe
it's not the perfect candidate

00:29:17.360 --> 00:29:19.480
to be going on public
transport just yet.

00:29:19.480 --> 00:29:21.840
So you have to almost
self-regulate a little bit.

00:29:21.840 --> 00:29:25.210
And we're very clear
in our messaging--

00:29:25.210 --> 00:29:27.800
this will only work if people
are responsible as well.

00:29:27.800 --> 00:29:29.390
But we are making progress.

00:29:29.390 --> 00:29:34.000
And for the simple
fact that, I think,

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:35.530
government does
recognize that there

00:29:35.530 --> 00:29:38.350
are some significant
benefits out there,

00:29:38.350 --> 00:29:45.470
and we have been caught behind,
really, the rest of the world.

00:29:45.470 --> 00:29:51.627
And if we are looking for people
to use more public transport,

00:29:51.627 --> 00:29:53.710
the people in the community--
it's not their fault

00:29:53.710 --> 00:29:55.085
that they don't
have a car, where

00:29:55.085 --> 00:29:57.910
we're trying to encourage people
to use public transport and not

00:29:57.910 --> 00:29:59.010
necessarily need cars.

00:29:59.010 --> 00:30:01.407
So that's got to include
the whole family,

00:30:01.407 --> 00:30:02.910
and that includes pets.

00:30:02.910 --> 00:30:04.500
And look, there are votes in it.

00:30:04.500 --> 00:30:07.110
At this simple level, I do
believe there are votes in it.

00:30:07.110 --> 00:30:12.622
I think people-- 67% of
people out there own a pet.

00:30:12.622 --> 00:30:15.490
So generally, people
aren't offended

00:30:15.490 --> 00:30:19.480
if we loosen up the regulations
around where pets can go.

00:30:19.480 --> 00:30:22.155
But people are really thrilled
if you do it for their animal.

00:30:22.155 --> 00:30:24.113
SPEAKER: You've mentioned
quite a few countries

00:30:24.113 --> 00:30:27.600
during your talk of where you've
seen this working really well.

00:30:27.600 --> 00:30:30.960
Are there countries that
have the best in class?

00:30:30.960 --> 00:30:33.620
Is it France, or is it--

00:30:33.620 --> 00:30:36.100
CHRIS BROWN: France
is pretty good.

00:30:36.100 --> 00:30:39.350
Yeah, like, northern
Europe is quite good.

00:30:39.350 --> 00:30:44.754
Canada is actually very
impressive, I find.

00:30:44.754 --> 00:30:45.670
Its across the border.

00:30:45.670 --> 00:30:48.440
It's in terms of
legislation, and it's

00:30:48.440 --> 00:30:55.760
in terms of how they influence
their registration practices

00:30:55.760 --> 00:30:57.725
with pets and micro-chipping
and de-sexing,

00:30:57.725 --> 00:30:58.760
and all the rest of it.

00:30:58.760 --> 00:31:03.240
But generally, northern Europe
and northern North America

00:31:03.240 --> 00:31:04.770
are where it's at.

00:31:04.770 --> 00:31:06.520
Further north you go,
the better it seems.

00:31:06.520 --> 00:31:08.269
SPEAKER: We had some
fun questions as well

00:31:08.269 --> 00:31:09.320
that came through.

00:31:09.320 --> 00:31:12.210
So Australia has many
unique animals, locally,

00:31:12.210 --> 00:31:13.960
but a lot of them, you
can't have as pets.

00:31:13.960 --> 00:31:19.290
This person listed a pet quoll,
a wombat, and a sugar glider,

00:31:19.290 --> 00:31:20.939
and asked, how can
we raise awareness

00:31:20.939 --> 00:31:23.480
of these beautiful animals, and
how can we change the laws so

00:31:23.480 --> 00:31:25.580
that they can also be pets?

00:31:25.580 --> 00:31:26.330
CHRIS BROWN: Yeah.

00:31:26.330 --> 00:31:27.530
SPEAKER: Where's the
line drawn, basically?

00:31:27.530 --> 00:31:28.613
CHRIS BROWN: Yeah, I know.

00:31:28.613 --> 00:31:29.430
It's a tricky one.

00:31:29.430 --> 00:31:31.846
Some of those animals that are
mentioned there-- the quoll

00:31:31.846 --> 00:31:34.442
is our native cat.

00:31:34.442 --> 00:31:34.942
Yeah.

00:31:34.942 --> 00:31:36.733
You want to be pretty
selective about which

00:31:36.733 --> 00:31:37.690
quoll you take home.

00:31:37.690 --> 00:31:40.110
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:40.110 --> 00:31:43.490
The thing we often forget
about with dogs and cats--

00:31:43.490 --> 00:31:45.210
and especially in
the case of dogs--

00:31:45.210 --> 00:31:48.110
is that they didn't
just turn up.

00:31:48.110 --> 00:31:49.880
We haven't just
decided one day that we

00:31:49.880 --> 00:31:51.275
want to keep a dog as a pet.

00:31:51.275 --> 00:31:54.416
We've been domesticating
dogs for 10,000 years.

00:31:54.416 --> 00:31:58.570
So they're such great pets
because we made them that way.

00:31:58.570 --> 00:32:03.000
And you wouldn't just grab a
wolf and expect to raise a wolf

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:05.800
puppy, and think that the wolf
puppy-- it'd be awesome, but--

00:32:05.800 --> 00:32:06.580
[LAUGHTER]

00:32:06.580 --> 00:32:08.520
SPEAKER: And dingoes
stole my baby stuff.

00:32:08.520 --> 00:32:08.930
CHRIS BROWN: Yeah.

00:32:08.930 --> 00:32:09.888
Well, that's the thing.

00:32:09.888 --> 00:32:11.590
Like, dingoes are
an example of that.

00:32:11.590 --> 00:32:15.795
They, generally, as a rule,
don't make great pets,

00:32:15.795 --> 00:32:17.170
because they're
not domesticated.

00:32:17.170 --> 00:32:19.470
And so we've chosen,
as the attributes--

00:32:19.470 --> 00:32:24.510
we've generally chosen the calm,
responsible, quieter ones that

00:32:24.510 --> 00:32:26.070
are affectionate.

00:32:26.070 --> 00:32:29.670
So to have quolls
or sugar gliders

00:32:29.670 --> 00:32:32.620
as pets-- you can get lucky.

00:32:32.620 --> 00:32:35.020
You can get one that's very
tame and very, very quiet,

00:32:35.020 --> 00:32:37.070
but as a general
rule, there's always

00:32:37.070 --> 00:32:39.405
going to be one in two or
one in three, at least,

00:32:39.405 --> 00:32:42.030
that's not going to be suitable
and might ruin it for everyone.

00:32:42.030 --> 00:32:43.090
SPEAKER: It's such
a shame, though,

00:32:43.090 --> 00:32:43.950
because sugar
gliders are so cute.

00:32:43.950 --> 00:32:44.760
CHRIS BROWN: They are.

00:32:44.760 --> 00:32:45.620
SPEAKER: At least,
they're around,

00:32:45.620 --> 00:32:46.877
and you can go and visit them.

00:32:46.877 --> 00:32:49.460
CHRIS BROWN: They're remarkably
popular in the States as well.

00:32:49.460 --> 00:32:49.710
SPEAKER: Really?

00:32:49.710 --> 00:32:50.440
CHRIS BROWN: People
actually have them

00:32:50.440 --> 00:32:51.356
as pets in the States.

00:32:51.356 --> 00:32:52.090
SPEAKER: Right.

00:32:52.090 --> 00:32:52.250
Yeah.

00:32:52.250 --> 00:32:53.530
Well, I think a
controversial question

00:32:53.530 --> 00:32:55.010
someone asked was about cats.

00:32:55.010 --> 00:32:56.502
So obviously, I,
sort of, prefaced

00:32:56.502 --> 00:32:57.960
by saying that
we're a dog company.

00:32:57.960 --> 00:33:01.030
But someone did ask, cats, while
being one of Australia's most

00:33:01.030 --> 00:33:04.010
favorite pets, are
hugely destructive

00:33:04.010 --> 00:33:06.567
to native Australian animals.

00:33:06.567 --> 00:33:08.150
And they suggest,
you know, how can we

00:33:08.150 --> 00:33:11.590
encourage people to make sure
their cats aren't roaming all

00:33:11.590 --> 00:33:13.570
the time, or to be more
responsible about how

00:33:13.570 --> 00:33:15.140
they deal with cats.

00:33:15.140 --> 00:33:16.890
CHRIS BROWN: I actually
think we give cats

00:33:16.890 --> 00:33:18.820
a hard time in this country.

00:33:18.820 --> 00:33:22.155
We're one of the few
developed nations--

00:33:22.155 --> 00:33:23.530
we might be the
only one or there

00:33:23.530 --> 00:33:26.670
might be one other
country-- where

00:33:26.670 --> 00:33:28.720
cat ownership is declining.

00:33:28.720 --> 00:33:30.470
In every other
country in the world,

00:33:30.470 --> 00:33:33.480
as we move into smaller
areas, into apartments,

00:33:33.480 --> 00:33:37.680
everyone else has recognized the
suitability of cats for that.

00:33:37.680 --> 00:33:39.600
And as a result, cat
numbers have increased,

00:33:39.600 --> 00:33:41.200
apart from in Australia.

00:33:41.200 --> 00:33:43.670
And I think it's the
wildlife thing that

00:33:43.670 --> 00:33:45.970
causes that, which is a shame.

00:33:45.970 --> 00:33:50.130
And certainly, cats are to blame
for a huge number of wildlife

00:33:50.130 --> 00:33:52.040
fatalities.

00:33:52.040 --> 00:33:54.360
When you look at the studies,
though, the vast majority

00:33:54.360 --> 00:33:56.726
of those are feral cats.

00:33:56.726 --> 00:34:01.800
Your domestic home cat accounts
for a small percentage of that.

00:34:01.800 --> 00:34:03.550
It's still too high, obviously.

00:34:03.550 --> 00:34:06.860
But that's why we're saying it's
part of being a responsible dog

00:34:06.860 --> 00:34:08.480
owner.

00:34:08.480 --> 00:34:11.280
You keep a fenced backyard.

00:34:11.280 --> 00:34:14.980
With a cat, keep them inside
or keep them in an enclosed cat

00:34:14.980 --> 00:34:17.460
area outside.

00:34:17.460 --> 00:34:19.790
If you do the responsible
thing, then there's

00:34:19.790 --> 00:34:22.210
no reason why cats
can't be as popular

00:34:22.210 --> 00:34:25.000
as dogs in this country.

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:26.770
They can be amazing,
amazing pets.

00:34:26.770 --> 00:34:29.969
I've got a cat, myself,
who was, to be fair,

00:34:29.969 --> 00:34:32.480
was raised with a dog
and thinks she is a dog.

00:34:32.480 --> 00:34:33.989
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:33.989 --> 00:34:36.199
And she's great.

00:34:36.199 --> 00:34:40.840
You know, and YouTube
can't be wrong.

00:34:40.840 --> 00:34:45.531
Look at how many cat videos that
are out there that are popular.

00:34:45.531 --> 00:34:49.472
I saw one last night of
kittens massaging each other.

00:34:49.472 --> 00:34:50.305
And that's adorable.

00:34:50.305 --> 00:34:50.960
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:50.960 --> 00:34:54.000
How can you not like that?

00:34:54.000 --> 00:34:57.340
My cat, Cricket, has an
obsessive compulsive massaging

00:34:57.340 --> 00:35:00.120
disorder, where,
if I leave her--

00:35:00.120 --> 00:35:03.120
if I don't-- she actually
doesn't sleep in my room,

00:35:03.120 --> 00:35:07.700
for one simple fact that at 2:00
AM, 3:00 AM, 4:00 AM, 5:00 AM,

00:35:07.700 --> 00:35:09.040
she massages.

00:35:09.040 --> 00:35:11.200
She gets into my room
and just sits there.

00:35:11.200 --> 00:35:12.147
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:12.147 --> 00:35:14.230
SPEAKER: She thinks she's
going to be of service--

00:35:14.230 --> 00:35:15.420
CHRIS BROWN: Like,
you're never more relaxed

00:35:15.420 --> 00:35:16.900
than you are at two
o'clock in the morning.

00:35:16.900 --> 00:35:18.940
I do not need a massage at
two o'clock in the morning.

00:35:18.940 --> 00:35:19.439
[LAUGHTER]

00:35:19.439 --> 00:35:20.284
SPEAKER: No.

00:35:20.284 --> 00:35:21.630
Fair.

00:35:21.630 --> 00:35:24.280
And on the point of these
social media stars-- like,

00:35:24.280 --> 00:35:25.603
I had a quick look.

00:35:25.603 --> 00:35:29.330
Jiffpom had a hoodie photo
that had hundreds of thousands

00:35:29.330 --> 00:35:29.930
of likes.

00:35:29.930 --> 00:35:33.530
And I looked at the
overbite of Tuna the Dog.

00:35:33.530 --> 00:35:35.510
How can we, sort of,
use-- if any of us

00:35:35.510 --> 00:35:37.760
have really cute pets or
big Instagram followers,

00:35:37.760 --> 00:35:41.560
how can help try and push this
forward, this sort of campaign?

00:35:41.560 --> 00:35:44.899
I've seen it's got hundreds
of posts on the hashtag,

00:35:44.899 --> 00:35:46.732
already on Instagram
and that sort of stuff.

00:35:46.732 --> 00:35:47.482
CHRIS BROWN: Yeah.

00:35:47.482 --> 00:35:50.410
I think-- how do you boost the
popularity of your own pets

00:35:50.410 --> 00:35:50.910
online?

00:35:50.910 --> 00:35:52.666
SPEAKER: Well,
that, too, but also

00:35:52.666 --> 00:35:55.040
to get people talking about
this idea of making Australia

00:35:55.040 --> 00:35:56.780
more pet-friendly and
that sort of thing.

00:35:56.780 --> 00:36:00.240
CHRIS BROWN: Look,
I think there's

00:36:00.240 --> 00:36:01.790
a real innocence
around our animals

00:36:01.790 --> 00:36:03.670
and I think this is
what they'd want.

00:36:03.670 --> 00:36:04.470
You know?

00:36:04.470 --> 00:36:07.610
They really would, and they're
clearly right behind it.

00:36:07.610 --> 00:36:10.992
And I just think that given
all the love and all benefits

00:36:10.992 --> 00:36:13.450
that they give us, I think it's
only fair that we give them

00:36:13.450 --> 00:36:14.455
something in return.

00:36:14.455 --> 00:36:16.830
And that's what the whole
pet-friendly campaign is about.

00:36:16.830 --> 00:36:18.380
It's just giving them something.

00:36:18.380 --> 00:36:20.640
And they actually
don't ask for a lot.

00:36:20.640 --> 00:36:26.280
And if we actually give the
dogs an off-leash area--

00:36:26.280 --> 00:36:29.140
those enclosed
areas-- the amount

00:36:29.140 --> 00:36:33.000
of energy they burn off in a
20-minutes run around there--

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:35.450
they'll generally sleep
for the rest of the day.

00:36:35.450 --> 00:36:38.269
So it's actually giving us
something back in return,

00:36:38.269 --> 00:36:39.810
in the way that
they're more content.

00:36:39.810 --> 00:36:41.350
They're less likely
to be stressed

00:36:41.350 --> 00:36:43.420
when we're away at work.

00:36:43.420 --> 00:36:45.320
So a lot of these
measures are not

00:36:45.320 --> 00:36:48.070
just about making Australia
more pet-friendly.

00:36:48.070 --> 00:36:50.060
They're actually about
our pets being more

00:36:50.060 --> 00:36:51.690
relaxed an better off as well.

00:36:51.690 --> 00:36:53.940
SPEAKER: Well, [INAUDIBLE]
questions in the room, too.

