00:37:51.926 --> 00:37:52.676
CHRIS BROWN: Yeah.

00:37:52.676 --> 00:37:56.120
So the push at the
moment-- the current rule

00:37:56.120 --> 00:37:59.400
is that it's up to the
landlord to decide,

00:37:59.400 --> 00:38:05.372
and that's unfortunately
almost the-- that block

00:38:05.372 --> 00:38:06.580
is the exception to the rule.

00:38:06.580 --> 00:38:09.380
I mean, generally, a
lot of apartment owners

00:38:09.380 --> 00:38:11.316
are saying, no.

00:38:11.316 --> 00:38:13.210
But what we're
trying to push for

00:38:13.210 --> 00:38:18.790
is to actually switch it
around so the landlord has

00:38:18.790 --> 00:38:21.980
to give a reason why not,
as opposed to you having

00:38:21.980 --> 00:38:24.760
to push your case as to why.

00:38:24.760 --> 00:38:26.780
And that's an
ongoing discussion,

00:38:26.780 --> 00:38:28.000
and it's a hard one.

00:38:28.000 --> 00:38:33.830
But what you're saying with
the height being the issue--

00:38:33.830 --> 00:38:36.160
even that is a
little frustrating.

00:38:36.160 --> 00:38:38.520
Because anyone that
knows dogs knows

00:38:38.520 --> 00:38:42.280
that a small dog like,
say, Jack Russell,

00:38:42.280 --> 00:38:45.720
will have more energy than
a big dog like a Great Dane,

00:38:45.720 --> 00:38:48.390
for example, and will
be, actually, probably,

00:38:48.390 --> 00:38:50.970
more inclined to bark
and more inclined to be

00:38:50.970 --> 00:38:52.630
destructive in an apartment.

00:38:52.630 --> 00:38:54.030
So it doesn't make sense.

00:38:54.030 --> 00:38:56.060
And that's probably
the frustration.

00:38:56.060 --> 00:38:59.085
It's that a lot of these
rules aren't based on fact,

00:38:59.085 --> 00:39:02.520
and aren't based on
science or research.

00:39:02.520 --> 00:39:05.040
And the only way you
can change these things

00:39:05.040 --> 00:39:07.620
is by actually having
face-to-face meetings

00:39:07.620 --> 00:39:11.430
and informing them in
a non-threatening way,

00:39:11.430 --> 00:39:16.202
as to why their policy
probably needs a bit of a look.

00:39:16.202 --> 00:39:17.660
SPEAKER: And a Jack
Russell doesn't

00:39:17.660 --> 00:39:18.640
know that it's a small dog.

00:39:18.640 --> 00:39:19.681
It thinks it's a big dog.

00:39:19.681 --> 00:39:20.342
You know?

00:39:20.342 --> 00:39:21.092
CHRIS BROWN: Yeah.

00:39:21.092 --> 00:39:22.180
Exactly.

00:39:22.180 --> 00:39:25.680
Generally, I know
a lot of big dogs

00:39:25.680 --> 00:39:28.000
that would be
happier in apartments

00:39:28.000 --> 00:39:31.100
than some small dogs, which
is, kind of, counter-intuitive,

00:39:31.100 --> 00:39:31.889
but it's true.

00:39:31.889 --> 00:39:32.930
AUDIENCE: Thanks, doctor.

00:39:32.930 --> 00:39:33.560
What are you--

00:39:33.560 --> 00:39:34.182
CHRIS BROWN: Thank you, Joe.

00:39:34.182 --> 00:39:34.682
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:34.682 --> 00:39:38.010
AUDIENCE: --wanting
the pet lovers to do?

00:39:38.010 --> 00:39:40.260
Is it to lobby their member
and get a bit more active?

00:39:40.260 --> 00:39:43.390
What are you actually wanting,
in terms of action from people?

00:39:43.390 --> 00:39:44.140
CHRIS BROWN: Yeah.

00:39:44.140 --> 00:39:45.015
It's a good question.

00:39:45.015 --> 00:39:46.960
Thanks, Joe.

00:39:46.960 --> 00:39:51.070
I think we're dealing
with politicians,

00:39:51.070 --> 00:39:55.360
so it's making them realize that
the votes are involved here.

00:39:55.360 --> 00:39:57.920
It's writing letters
to the newspaper.

00:39:57.920 --> 00:40:01.050
The Telegraph has
been right behind,

00:40:01.050 --> 00:40:03.420
trying to stir up the
issue with the pets

00:40:03.420 --> 00:40:06.470
in the pubs in the Inner West.

00:40:06.470 --> 00:40:08.650
They love opinion pieces
because they realize

00:40:08.650 --> 00:40:10.130
that it's a passionate topic.

00:40:10.130 --> 00:40:12.760
And so get involved.

00:40:12.760 --> 00:40:16.500
Start lobbying people, yourself.

00:40:16.500 --> 00:40:19.330
Use the Keep Australia
Pet-Friendly hashtag

00:40:19.330 --> 00:40:22.810
on your social media posts.

00:40:22.810 --> 00:40:24.850
And certainly, keep
all the feedback

00:40:24.850 --> 00:40:27.537
coming around on what
is important to you

00:40:27.537 --> 00:40:28.370
and your local area.

00:40:28.370 --> 00:40:31.260
Because we're in a
fortunate position

00:40:31.260 --> 00:40:34.550
where we can collate that and
actually make presentations

00:40:34.550 --> 00:40:35.190
to government.

00:40:35.190 --> 00:40:38.110
But if it's more than just
us that's in their ear,

00:40:38.110 --> 00:40:40.980
if it's actually members
of their own electorates,

00:40:40.980 --> 00:40:43.760
then it's a lot more powerful.

00:40:43.760 --> 00:40:47.720
We met with the heads of local
government a couple of months

00:40:47.720 --> 00:40:50.340
ago, so all the mayors
and local councils

00:40:50.340 --> 00:40:51.340
from around the country.

00:40:51.340 --> 00:40:54.000
And in the one month
since that meeting,

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:57.670
they've put in eight new
off-leash area parks.

00:40:57.670 --> 00:41:00.880
They do listen, but
their big feedback

00:41:00.880 --> 00:41:02.940
was, they didn't
understand why there

00:41:02.940 --> 00:41:05.190
was this buzz around
off-leash area parks.

00:41:05.190 --> 00:41:07.460
They didn't really understand
why they are important.

00:41:07.460 --> 00:41:09.550
And it just takes people
to sit down with them

00:41:09.550 --> 00:41:12.010
and explain the
benefits for them

00:41:12.010 --> 00:41:14.510
to go, oh, OK, so that's
why they want the fences,

00:41:14.510 --> 00:41:17.300
because we couldn't work out
why they wanted the fences.

00:41:17.300 --> 00:41:19.300
We thought that it always
looked strange to have

00:41:19.300 --> 00:41:21.466
a fence in there, but that's
actually what you want.

00:41:21.466 --> 00:41:22.460
OK, all right.

00:41:22.460 --> 00:41:25.580
And a lot of those
parks came about

00:41:25.580 --> 00:41:28.505
because people were lobbying
their local government.

00:41:28.505 --> 00:41:31.200
They were starting up petitions.

00:41:31.200 --> 00:41:36.030
Even just those Change.orgs,
those online petitions--

00:41:36.030 --> 00:41:39.460
it's amazing the amount
of support they get.

00:41:39.460 --> 00:41:41.930
If you can present a couple
of hundred signatures

00:41:41.930 --> 00:41:45.460
to your local government or a
couple of thousand signatures

00:41:45.460 --> 00:41:48.880
to a state government,
they start to listen.

00:41:48.880 --> 00:41:50.440
SPEAKER: A local
council and park

00:41:50.440 --> 00:41:53.567
at a time, and then
hopefully, more will join.

